# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: intel-sgx
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] In computing, a **cache** (/kæʃ/ ⓘ *KASH*) is a hardware or software component that stores data so that future requests for that data can be served faster; the data stored in a cache might be the result of an earlier computation or a copy of data stored elsewhere.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A **cache hit** occurs when the requested data can be found in a cache, while a **cache miss** occurs when it cannot.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Cache hits are served by reading data from the cache, which is faster than recomputing a result or reading from a slower data store; thus, the more requests that can be served from the cache, the faster the system performs.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] To be cost-effective, caches must be relatively small.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Nevertheless, caches are effective in many areas of computing because typical computer applications access data with a high degree of locality of reference.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Such access patterns exhibit temporal locality, where data is requested that has been recently requested, and spatial locality, where data is requested that is stored near data that has already been requested.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] In memory design, there is an inherent trade-off between capacity and speed because larger capacity implies larger size and thus greater physical distances for signals to travel causing propagation delays.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] There is also a tradeoff between high-performance technologies such as SRAM and cheaper, easily mass-produced commodities such as DRAM, flash, or hard disks.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The buffering provided by a cache benefits one or both of latency and throughput (bandwidth).
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A larger resource incurs a significant latency for access – e.g. it can take hundreds of clock cycles for a modern 4 GHz processor to reach DRAM.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] This is mitigated by reading large chunks into the cache, in the hope that subsequent reads will be from nearby locations and can be read from the cache.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Prediction or explicit prefetching can be used to guess where future reads will come from and make requests ahead of time; if done optimally, the latency is bypassed altogether.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The use of a cache also allows for higher throughput from the underlying resource, by assembling multiple fine-grain transfers into larger, more efficient requests.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] In the case of DRAM circuits, the additional throughput may be gained by using a wider data bus.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Hardware implements cache as a block of memory for temporary storage of data likely to be used again.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Central processing units (CPUs), solid-state drives (SSDs) and hard disk drives (HDDs) frequently include hardware-based cache, while web browsers and web servers commonly rely on software caching.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A cache is made up of a pool of entries.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Each entry has associated *data*, which is a copy of the same data in some *backing store*.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Each entry also has a *tag*, which specifies the identity of the data in the backing store of which the entry is a copy.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] When the cache client (a CPU, web browser, operating system) needs to access data presumed to exist in the backing store, it first checks the cache.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] If an entry can be found with a tag matching that of the desired data, the data in the entry is used instead.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] This situation is known as a **cache hit**.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] For example, a web browser program might check its local cache on disk to see if it has a local copy of the contents of a web page at a particular URL.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] In this example, the URL is the tag, and the content of the web page is the data.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The percentage of accesses that result in cache hits is known as the **hit rate** or **hit ratio** of the cache.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The alternative situation, when the cache is checked and found not to contain any entry with the desired tag, is known as a **cache miss**.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] This requires a more expensive access of data from the backing store.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Once the requested data is retrieved, it is typically copied into the cache, ready for the next access.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] During a cache miss, some other previously existing cache entry is typically removed in order to make room for the newly retrieved data.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The heuristic used to select the entry to replace is known as the replacement policy.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] One popular replacement policy, least recently used (LRU), replaces the oldest entry, the entry that was accessed less recently than any other entry.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] More sophisticated caching algorithms also take into account the frequency of use of entries.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Cache writes must eventually be propagated to the backing store.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The timing for this is governed by the *write policy*.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A write-back cache is more complex to implement since it needs to track which of its locations have been written over and mark them as *dirty* for later writing to the backing store.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The data in these locations are written back to the backing store only when they are evicted from the cache, a process referred to as a *lazy write*.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] For this reason, a read miss in a write-back cache may require two memory accesses to the backing store: one to write back the dirty data, and one to retrieve the requested data.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Other policies may also trigger data write-back.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The client may make many changes to data in the cache, and then explicitly notify the cache to write back the data.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Consequently, a decision needs to be made for write misses: whether or not to load the data into the cache.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Entities other than the cache may change the data in the backing store, in which case the copy in the cache may become out-of-date or *stale*.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Alternatively, when the client updates the data in the cache, copies of that data in other caches will become stale.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Communication protocols between the cache managers that keep the data consistent are associated with cache coherence.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] On a cache read miss, caches with a *demand paging policy* read the minimum amount from the backing store.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A typical demand-paging virtual memory implementation reads one page of virtual memory (often 4 KB) from disk into the disk cache in RAM.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A typical CPU reads a single L2 cache line of 128 bytes from DRAM into the L2 cache, and a single L1 cache line of 64 bytes from the L2 cache into the L1 cache.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Caches with a prefetch input queue or more general *anticipatory paging policy* go further—they not only read the data requested, but guess that the next chunk or two of data will soon be required, and so prefetch that data into the cache ahead of time.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Anticipatory paging is especially helpful when the backing store has a long latency to read the first chunk and much shorter times to sequentially read the next few chunks, such as disk storage and DRAM.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A few operating systems go further with a loader that always pre-loads the entire executable into RAM.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A few caches go even further, not only pre-loading an entire file, but also starting to load other related files that may soon be requested, such as the page cache associated with a prefetcher or the web cache associated with link prefetching.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Small memories on or close to the CPU can operate faster than the much larger main memory.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Most CPUs since the 1980s have used one or more caches, sometimes in cascaded levels; modern high-end embedded, desktop and server microprocessors may have as many as six types of cache (between levels and functions).
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Some examples of caches with a specific function are the D-cache, I-cache and the translation lookaside buffer for the memory management unit (MMU).
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Earlier graphics processing units (GPUs) often had limited read-only texture caches and used swizzling to improve 2D locality of reference.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Cache misses would drastically affect performance, e.g. if mipmapping was not used.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Caching was important to leverage 32-bit (and wider) transfers for texture data that was often as little as 4 bits per pixel.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] As GPUs advanced, supporting general-purpose computing on graphics processing units and compute kernels, they have developed progressively larger and increasingly general caches, including instruction caches for shaders, exhibiting functionality commonly found in CPU caches.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] These caches have grown to handle synchronization primitives between threads and atomic operations, and interface with a CPU-style MMU.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Digital signal processors have similarly generalized over the years.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Earlier designs used scratchpad memory fed by direct memory access; modern DSPs often include a very similar set of caches to a CPU (e.g.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Modified Harvard architecture with shared L2, split L1 I-cache and D-cache).
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A memory management unit (MMU) that fetches page table entries from main memory has a specialized cache, used for recording the results of virtual address to physical address translations.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] This specialized cache is called a translation lookaside buffer (TLB).
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Information-centric networking (ICN) is an approach to evolve the Internet infrastructure away from a host-centric paradigm, based on perpetual connectivity and the end-to-end principle, to a network architecture in which the focal point is identified information.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Due to the inherent caching capability of the nodes in an ICN, it can be viewed as a loosely connected network of caches, which has unique requirements for caching policies.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] However, ubiquitous content caching introduces the challenge to content protection against unauthorized access, which requires extra care and solutions.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Unlike proxy servers, in ICN the cache is a network-level solution.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Therefore, it has rapidly changing cache states and higher request arrival rates; moreover, smaller cache sizes impose different requirements on the content eviction policies.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] In particular, eviction policies for ICN should be fast and lightweight.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Various cache replication and eviction schemes for different ICN architectures and applications have been proposed.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The time aware least recently used (TLRU) is a variant of LRU designed for the situation where the stored contents in cache have a valid lifetime.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The algorithm is suitable in network cache applications, such as ICN, content delivery networks (CDNs) and distributed networks in general.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] TLRU introduces a new term: time to use (TTU).
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] TTU is a time stamp on content which stipulates the usability time for the content based on the locality of the content and information from the content publisher.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Owing to this locality-based time stamp, TTU provides more control to the local administrator to regulate in-network storage.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] In the TLRU algorithm, when a piece of content arrives, a cache node calculates the local TTU value based on the TTU value assigned by the content publisher.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The local TTU value is calculated by using a locally defined function.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Once the local TTU value is calculated the replacement of content is performed on a subset of the total content stored in cache node.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The TLRU ensures that less popular and short-lived content should be replaced with incoming content.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The least frequent recently used (LFRU) cache replacement scheme combines the benefits of LFU and LRU schemes.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] LFRU is suitable for network cache applications, such as ICN, CDNs and distributed networks in general.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] In LFRU, the cache is divided into two partitions called privileged and unprivileged partitions.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The privileged partition can be seen as a protected partition.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] If content is highly popular, it is pushed into the privileged partition.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Replacement of the privileged partition is done by first evicting content from the unprivileged partition, then pushing content from the privileged partition to the unprivileged partition, and finally inserting new content into the privileged partition.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] In the above procedure, the LRU is used for the privileged partition and an approximated LFU (ALFU) scheme is used for the unprivileged partition.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The basic idea is to cache the locally popular content with the ALFU scheme and push the popular content to the privileged partition.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] In 2011, the use of smartphones with weather forecasting options was overly taxing AccuWeather servers; two requests from the same area would generate separate requests.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] An optimization by edge-servers to truncate the GPS coordinates to fewer decimal places meant that the cached results from a nearby query would be used.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The number of to-the-server lookups per day dropped by half.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] While CPU caches are generally managed entirely by hardware, a variety of software manages other caches.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The page cache in main memory is managed by the operating system kernel.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] While the disk buffer, which is an integrated part of the hard disk drive or solid state drive, is sometimes misleadingly referred to as *disk cache*, its main functions are write sequencing and read prefetching.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] High-end disk controllers often have their own on-board cache for the hard disk drive's data blocks.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Finally, a fast local hard disk drive can also cache information held on even slower data storage devices, such as remote servers (web cache) or local tape drives or optical jukeboxes; such a scheme is the main concept of hierarchical storage management.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Also, fast flash-based solid-state drives (SSDs) can be used as caches for slower rotational-media hard disk drives, working together as hybrid drives.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Web browsers and web proxy servers, either locally or at the Internet service provider (ISP), employ web caches to store previous responses from web servers, such as web pages and images.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Web caches reduce the amount of information that needs to be transmitted across the network, as information previously stored in the cache can often be re-used.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] This reduces bandwidth and processing requirements of the web server, and helps to improve responsiveness for users of the web.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Another form of cache is P2P caching, where the files most sought for by peer-to-peer applications are stored in an ISP cache to accelerate P2P transfers.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Similarly, decentralised equivalents exist, which allow communities to perform the same task for P2P traffic, for example, Corelli.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A cache can store data that is computed on demand rather than retrieved from a backing store.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Memoization is an optimization technique that stores the results of resource-consuming function calls within a lookup table, allowing subsequent calls to reuse the stored results and avoid repeated computation.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] It is related to the dynamic programming algorithm design methodology, which can also be thought of as a means of caching.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A content delivery network (CDN) is a network of distributed servers that deliver pages and other web content to a user, based on the geographic locations of the user, the origin of the web page and the content delivery server.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] CDNs were introduced in the late 1990s as a way to speed up the delivery of static content, such as HTML pages, images and videos.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] By replicating content on multiple servers around the world and delivering it to users based on their location, CDNs can significantly improve the speed and availability of a website or application.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] When a user requests a piece of content, the CDN will check to see if it has a copy of the content in its cache.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] If it does, the CDN will deliver the content to the user from the cache.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A cloud storage gateway is a hybrid cloud storage device that connects a local network to one or more cloud storage services, typically object storage services such as Amazon S3.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] It provides a cache for frequently accessed data, providing high speed local access to frequently accessed data in the cloud storage service.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Cloud storage gateways also provide additional benefits such as accessing cloud object storage through traditional file serving protocols as well as continued access to cached data during connectivity outages.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A DNS cache caches a mapping of domain names to IP addresses.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Examples of services providing such caches include the BIND daemon and caching DNS resolver libraries.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Write-through operation is common when operating over unreliable networks, because of the enormous complexity of the coherency protocol required between multiple write-back caches when communication is unreliable.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] For instance, web page caches and client-side caches for distributed file systems (like those in NFS or SMB) are typically read-only or write-through specifically to keep the network protocol simple and reliable.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Web search engines also frequently make web pages they have indexed available from their cache.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] This can prove useful when web pages from a web server are temporarily or permanently inaccessible.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Database caching can substantially improve the throughput of database applications, for example in the processing of indexes, data dictionaries, and frequently used subsets of data.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A distributed cache uses networked hosts to provide scalability, reliability and performance to the application.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The hosts can be co-located or spread over different geographical regions.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Android Runtime and Common Language Runtime are examples that utilize storage-based JIT caches.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] GPU drivers usually utilize storage-based shader caches.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] The semantics of a *buffer* and a *cache* are not totally different; even so, there are fundamental differences in intent between the process of caching and the process of buffering.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Fundamentally, caching realizes a performance increase for transfers of data that is being repeatedly transferred.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] With read caches, a data item must have been fetched from its residing location at least once in order for subsequent reads of the data item to realize a performance increase by virtue of being able to be fetched from the cache's faster intermediate storage rather than the data's residing location.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Contrary to strict buffering, a caching process must adhere to a potentially distributed cache coherency protocol in order to maintain consistency between the cache's intermediate storage and the location where the data resides.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Buffering, on the other hand, reduces the number of transfers for otherwise novel data amongst communicating processes, which amortizes the overhead involved for several small transfers over fewer, larger transfers.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] It also provides an intermediary for communicating processes that are incapable of direct transfers amongst each other, or ensures a minimum data size or representation required by at least one of the communicating processes involved in a transfer.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] With typical caching implementations, a data item that is read or written for the first time is effectively being buffered.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Caching almost always involves some form of buffering, while strict buffering does not necessarily involve caching.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A buffer is a temporary memory location that is traditionally used because CPU instructions cannot directly address data stored in peripheral devices.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Thus, addressable memory is used as an intermediate stage.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Additionally, such a buffer may be required when a large block of data is assembled or disassembled (as required by a storage device), or when data may be delivered in a different order than that in which it is produced.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Also, a whole buffer of data is usually transferred sequentially (for example, to hard disk), so buffering itself sometimes increases transfer performance or reduces the variation or jitter of the transfer's latency as opposed to caching where the intent is to reduce the latency.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] These benefits are present even if the buffered data are written to the buffer once and read from the buffer once.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A cache also increases transfer performance.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A part of the increase similarly comes from the possibility that multiple small transfers will be combined into one large transfer.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] But the main performance gain occurs because there is a good chance that the same data will be read from cache multiple times, or that written data will soon be read.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] A cache's sole purpose is to reduce accesses to the underlying slower storage.
[src:intel-sgx/cache-computing] Cache is also usually an abstraction layer that is designed to be invisible from the perspective of neighboring layers.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] A **central processing unit** (**CPU**), also known as a **central processor**, **main processor**, or simply **processor**, is the primary processor in a given computer.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Its electronic circuitry executes instructions of a computer program, such as arithmetic, logic, controlling, and input/output (I/O) operations.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] This role contrasts with that of external components, such as main memory and I/O circuitry, and specialized coprocessors such as graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The form, design, and implementation of CPUs have changed over time, but their fundamental operation remains almost unchanged.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Modern CPUs devote a lot of semiconductor area to caches and instruction-level parallelism to increase performance and to CPU modes to support operating systems and virtualization.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Most modern CPUs are implemented on integrated circuit (IC) microprocessors, with one or more CPUs on a single IC chip.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Microprocessor chips with multiple CPUs are called *multi-core processors* (*MCPs*).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The individual physical CPUs, called *processor cores*, can also be multithreaded to support CPU-level multithreading.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] An IC that contains a CPU may also contain memory, peripheral interfaces, and other components of a computer; such integrated devices are variously called microcontrollers or systems on chip (SoCs).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Early computers such as the ENIAC had to be physically rewired to perform different tasks, which caused these machines to be called "fixed-program computers".
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The "central processing unit" term has been in use since as early as 1955.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Since the term "CPU" is generally defined as a device for software (computer program) execution, the earliest devices that could rightly be called CPUs came with the advent of the stored-program computer.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The idea of a stored-program computer had already been present in the design of John Presper Eckert and John William Mauchly's ENIAC, but was initially omitted so that it could be finished sooner.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] On June 30, 1945, before ENIAC was made, mathematician John von Neumann distributed a paper entitled *First Draft of a Report on the EDVAC*.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] It was the outline of a stored-program computer that would eventually be completed in August 1949.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] EDVAC was designed to perform a certain number of instructions (or operations) of various types.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Significantly, the programs written for EDVAC were to be stored in high-speed computer memory rather than specified by the physical wiring of the computer.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] This overcame a severe limitation of ENIAC, which was the considerable time and effort required to reconfigure the computer to perform a new task.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] With von Neumann's design, the program that EDVAC ran could be changed simply by changing the contents of the memory.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] EDVAC was not the first stored-program computer; the Manchester Baby, which was a small-scale experimental stored-program computer, ran its first program on 21 June 1948 and the Manchester Mark 1 ran its first program during the night of 16–17 June 1949.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Early CPUs were custom designs used as part of a larger and sometimes distinctive computer.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] However, this method of designing custom CPUs for a particular application has largely given way to the development of multi-purpose processors produced in large quantities.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] This standardization began in the era of discrete transistor mainframes and minicomputers, and has rapidly accelerated with the popularization of the integrated circuit (IC).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The IC has allowed increasingly complex CPUs to be designed and manufactured to tolerances on the order of nanometers.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Both the miniaturization and standardization of CPUs have increased the presence of digital devices in modern life far beyond the limited application of dedicated computing machines.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Modern microprocessors appear in electronic devices ranging from automobiles to cellphones, and sometimes even in toys.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] While von Neumann is most often credited with the design of the stored-program computer because of his design of EDVAC, and the design became known as the von Neumann architecture, others before him, such as Konrad Zuse, had suggested and implemented similar ideas.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The so-called Harvard architecture of the Harvard Mark I, which was completed before EDVAC, also used a stored-program design using punched paper tape rather than electronic memory.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The key difference between the two is that Harvard architecture separates the storage and treatment of CPU instructions and data, whereas von Neumann architecture uses the same memory space for both.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Most modern CPUs are primarily von Neumann in design, but CPUs with the Harvard architecture are seen as well, especially in embedded applications; for instance, the Atmel AVR microcontrollers are Harvard-architecture processors.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Prior to the invention of the transistor, relays and vacuum tubes (thermionic tubes) were commonly used as switching elements; a useful computer requires thousands or tens of thousands of switching devices.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The overall speed of a system is dependent on the speed of the switches.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Vacuum-tube computers such as EDVAC tended to average eight hours between failures, whereas relay computers—such as the slower but earlier Harvard Mark I—failed very rarely.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] In the end, tube-based CPUs became dominant because the significant speed advantages afforded generally outweighed the reliability problems.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Most of these early synchronous CPUs ran at low clock rates compared to modern microelectronic designs.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Clock signal frequencies ranging from 100 kHz to 4 MHz were very common at this time, limited largely by the speed of the switching devices they were built with.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The design complexity of CPUs increased as various technologies facilitated the building of smaller and more reliable electronic devices.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The first such improvement came with the advent of the transistor.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Transistorized CPUs during the 1950s and 1960s no longer had to be built out of bulky, unreliable, and fragile switching elements, like vacuum tubes and relays.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] With this improvement, more complex and reliable CPUs were built onto one or several printed circuit boards containing discrete (individual) components.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] In 1964, IBM introduced its IBM System/360 computer architecture that was used in a series of computers capable of running the same programs with different speeds and performances.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] This was significant at a time when most electronic computers were incompatible with one another, even those made by the same manufacturer.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] To facilitate this improvement, IBM used the concept of a microprogram (often called "microcode"), which still sees widespread use in modern CPUs.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The System/360 architecture was so popular that it dominated the mainframe computer market for decades and left a legacy that is continued by similar modern computers like the IBM zSeries.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] In 1965, Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) introduced another influential computer aimed at the scientific and research markets—the PDP-8.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Transistor-based computers had several distinct advantages over their predecessors.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Aside from facilitating increased reliability and lower power consumption, transistors also allowed CPUs to operate at much higher speeds because of the short switching time of a transistor in comparison to a tube or relay.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The increased reliability and dramatically increased speed of the switching elements, which were almost exclusively transistors by this time; CPU clock rates in the tens of megahertz were easily obtained during this period.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Additionally, while discrete transistor and IC CPUs were in heavy usage, new high-performance designs like single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) vector processors began to appear.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] These early experimental designs later gave rise to the era of specialized supercomputers like those made by Cray Inc and Fujitsu Ltd.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] During this period, a method of manufacturing many interconnected transistors in a compact space was developed.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The integrated circuit (IC) allowed a large number of transistors to be manufactured on a single semiconductor-based die, or "chip".
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] At first, only very basic non-specialized digital circuits such as NOR gates were miniaturized into ICs.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] CPUs based on these "building block" ICs are generally referred to as "small-scale integration" (SSI) devices.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] SSI ICs, such as the ones used in the Apollo Guidance Computer, usually contained up to a few dozen transistors.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] To build an entire CPU out of SSI ICs required thousands of individual chips, but still consumed much less space and power than earlier discrete transistor designs.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] IBM's System/370, follow-on to the System/360, used SSI ICs rather than Solid Logic Technology discrete-transistor modules.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] DEC's PDP-8/I and KI10 PDP-10 also switched from the individual transistors used by the PDP-8 and KA PDP-10 to SSI ICs, and their extremely popular PDP-11 line was originally built with SSI ICs, but was eventually implemented with LSI components once these became practical.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Lee Boysel published influential articles, including a 1967 "manifesto", which described how to build the equivalent of a 32-bit mainframe computer from a relatively small number of large-scale integration circuits (LSI).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The only way to build LSI chips, which are chips with a hundred or more gates, was to build them using a metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) semiconductor manufacturing process (either PMOS logic, NMOS logic, or CMOS logic).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] However, some companies continued to build processors out of bipolar transistor–transistor logic (TTL) chips because bipolar junction transistors were faster than MOS chips up until the 1970s (a few companies such as Datapoint continued to build processors out of TTL chips until the early 1980s).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] In the 1960s, MOS ICs were slower and initially considered useful only in applications that required low power.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Following the development of silicon-gate MOS technology by Federico Faggin at Fairchild Semiconductor in 1968, MOS ICs largely replaced bipolar TTL as the standard chip technology in the late 1970s.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] As the microelectronic technology advanced, an increasing number of transistors were placed on ICs, decreasing the number of individual ICs needed for a complete CPU.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] MSI and LSI ICs increased transistor counts to hundreds, and then thousands.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] By 1968, the number of ICs required to build a complete CPU had been reduced to 24 ICs of eight different types, with each IC containing roughly 1000 MOSFETs.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] In stark contrast with its SSI and MSI predecessors, the first LSI implementation of the PDP-11 contained a CPU composed of only four LSI integrated circuits.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Since microprocessors were first introduced they have almost completely overtaken all other central processing unit implementation methods.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The first commercially available microprocessor, made in 1971, was the Intel 4004.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The Intel 4004 was one of the first consumer-facing CPUs integrating arithmetic logic unit, control unit, and register unit on a chip.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The first widely used microprocessor, made in 1974, was the Intel 8080.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Mainframe and minicomputer manufacturers of the time launched proprietary IC development programs to upgrade their older computer architectures, and eventually produced instruction set compatible microprocessors that were backward-compatible with their older hardware and software.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Combined with the advent and eventual success of the ubiquitous personal computer, the term *CPU* is now applied almost exclusively to microprocessors.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Several CPUs (denoted *cores*) can be combined in a single processing chip.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Previous generations of CPUs were implemented as discrete components and numerous small integrated circuits (ICs) on one or more circuit boards.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Microprocessors, on the other hand, are CPUs manufactured on a very small number of ICs; usually just one.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The overall smaller CPU size, as a result of being implemented on a single die, means faster switching time because of physical factors like decreased gate parasitic capacitance.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] This has allowed synchronous microprocessors to have clock rates ranging from tens of megahertz to several gigahertz.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Additionally, the ability to construct exceedingly small transistors on an IC has increased the complexity and number of transistors in a single CPU many fold.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] This widely observed trend is described by Moore's law, which had proven to be a fairly accurate predictor of the growth of CPU (and other IC) complexity until 2016.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] While the complexity, size, construction and general form of CPUs have changed enormously since 1950, the basic design and function has not changed much at all.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Almost all common CPUs today can be very accurately described as von Neumann stored-program machines.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] As Moore's law no longer holds, concerns have arisen about the limits of integrated circuit transistor technology.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Extreme miniaturization of electronic gates is causing the effects of phenomena like electromigration and subthreshold leakage to become much more significant.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] These newer concerns are among the many factors causing researchers to investigate new methods of computing such as the quantum computer, as well as to expand the use of parallelism and other methods that extend the usefulness of the classical von Neumann model.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The fundamental operation of most CPUs, regardless of the physical form they take, is to execute a sequence of stored instructions that is called a program.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The instructions to be executed are kept in some kind of computer memory.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Nearly all CPUs follow the fetch, decode and execute steps in their operation, which are collectively known as the instruction cycle.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] After the execution of an instruction, the entire process repeats, with the next instruction cycle normally fetching the next-in-sequence instruction because of the incremented value in the program counter.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] If a jump instruction was executed, the program counter will be modified to contain the address of the instruction that was jumped to and program execution continues normally.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] In more complex CPUs, multiple instructions can be fetched, decoded and executed simultaneously.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] This section describes what is generally referred to as the "classic RISC pipeline", which is quite common among the simple CPUs used in many electronic devices (often called microcontrollers).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] It largely ignores the important role of CPU cache, and therefore the access stage of the pipeline.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Some instructions manipulate the program counter rather than producing result data directly; such instructions are generally called "jumps" and facilitate program behavior like loops, conditional program execution (through the use of a conditional jump), and existence of functions.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] In some processors, some other instructions change the state of bits in a "flags" register.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] These flags can be used to influence how a program behaves, since they often indicate the outcome of various operations.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] For example, in such processors a "compare" instruction evaluates two values and sets or clears bits in the flags register to indicate which one is greater or whether they are equal; one of these flags could then be used by a later jump instruction to determine program flow.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Fetch involves retrieving an instruction (which is represented by a number or sequence of numbers) from program memory.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The instruction's location (address) in program memory is determined by the program counter (PC; called the "instruction pointer" in Intel x86 microprocessors), which stores a number that identifies the address of the next instruction to be fetched.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] After an instruction is fetched, the PC is incremented by the length of the instruction so that it will contain the address of the next instruction in the sequence.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Often, the instruction to be fetched must be retrieved from relatively slow memory, causing the CPU to stall while waiting for the instruction to be returned.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] This issue is largely addressed in modern processors by caches and pipeline architectures (see below).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The instruction that the CPU fetches from memory determines what the CPU will do.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] In the decode step, performed by binary decoder circuitry known as the *instruction decoder*, the instruction is converted into signals that control other parts of the CPU.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The way in which the instruction is interpreted is defined by the CPU's instruction set architecture (ISA).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Often, one group of bits (that is, a "field") within the instruction, called the opcode, indicates which operation is to be performed, while the remaining fields usually provide supplemental information required for the operation, such as the operands.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Those operands may be specified as a constant value (called an immediate value), or as the location of a value that may be a processor register or a memory address, as determined by some addressing mode.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] In some CPU designs, the instruction decoder is implemented as a hardwired, unchangeable binary decoder circuit.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] In others, a microprogram is used to translate instructions into sets of CPU configuration signals that are applied sequentially over multiple clock pulses.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] In some cases the memory that stores the microprogram is rewritable, making it possible to change the way in which the CPU decodes instructions.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] After the fetch and decode steps, the execute step is performed.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Depending on the CPU architecture, this may consist of a single action or a sequence of actions.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] During each action, control signals electrically enable or disable various parts of the CPU so they can perform all or part of the desired operation.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] The action is then completed, typically in response to a clock pulse.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] Very often the results are written to an internal CPU register for quick access by subsequent instructions.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] In other cases results may be written to slower, but less expensive and higher capacity main memory.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] For example, if an instruction that performs addition is to be executed, registers containing operands (numbers to be summed) are activated, as are the parts of the arithmetic logic unit (ALU) that perform addition.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] When the clock pulse occurs, the operands flow from the source registers into the ALU, and the sum appears at its output.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] On subsequent clock pulses, other components are enabled (and disabled) to move the output (the sum of the operation) to storage (e.g., a register or memory).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p01] If the resulting sum is too large (i.e., it is larger than the ALU's output word size), an arithmetic overflow flag will be set, influencing the next operation.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Hardwired into a CPU's circuitry is a set of basic operations it can perform, called an instruction set.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Such operations may involve, for example, adding or subtracting two numbers, comparing two numbers, or jumping to a different part of a program.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Each instruction is represented by a unique combination of bits, known as the machine language opcode.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] While processing an instruction, the CPU decodes the opcode (via a binary decoder) into control signals, which orchestrate the behavior of the CPU.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] A complete machine language instruction consists of an opcode and, in many cases, additional bits that specify arguments for the operation (for example, the numbers to be summed in the case of an addition operation).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Going up the complexity scale, a machine language program is a collection of machine language instructions that the CPU executes.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The actual mathematical operation for each instruction is performed by a combinational logic circuit within the CPU's processor known as the arithmetic–logic unit or ALU.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] In general, a CPU executes an instruction by fetching it from memory, using its ALU to perform an operation, and then storing the result to memory.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The control unit (CU) is a component of the CPU that directs the operation of the processor.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] It tells the computer's memory, arithmetic and logic unit and input and output devices how to respond to the instructions that have been sent to the processor.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] It directs the operation of the other units by providing timing and control signals.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Most computer resources are managed by the CU.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] It directs the flow of data between the CPU and the other devices.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] John von Neumann included the control unit as part of the von Neumann architecture.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] In modern computer designs, the control unit is typically an internal part of the CPU with its overall role and operation unchanged since its introduction.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The arithmetic logic unit (ALU) is a digital circuit within the processor that performs integer arithmetic and bitwise logic operations.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The inputs to the ALU are the data words to be operated on (called operands), status information from previous operations, and a code from the control unit indicating which operation to perform.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Depending on the instruction being executed, the operands may come from internal CPU registers, external memory, or constants generated by the ALU itself.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] When all input signals have settled and propagated through the ALU circuitry, the result of the performed operation appears at the ALU's outputs.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The result consists of both a data word, which may be stored in a register or memory, and status information that is typically stored in a special, internal CPU register reserved for this purpose.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Modern CPUs typically contain more than one ALU to improve performance.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The address generation unit (AGU), sometimes also called the address computation unit (ACU), is an execution unit inside the CPU that calculates addresses used by the CPU to access main memory.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] By having address calculations handled by separate circuitry that operates in parallel with the rest of the CPU, the number of CPU cycles required for executing various machine instructions can be reduced, bringing performance improvements.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] While performing various operations, CPUs need to calculate memory addresses required for fetching data from the memory; for example, in-memory positions of array elements must be calculated before the CPU can fetch the data from actual memory locations.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Those address-generation calculations involve different integer arithmetic operations, such as addition, subtraction, modulo operations, or bit shifts.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Often, calculating a memory address involves more than one general-purpose machine instruction, which do not necessarily decode and execute quickly.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] By incorporating an AGU into a CPU design, together with introducing specialized instructions that use the AGU, various address-generation calculations can be offloaded from the rest of the CPU, and can often be executed quickly in a single CPU cycle.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Capabilities of an AGU depend on a particular CPU and its architecture.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Thus, some AGUs implement and expose more address-calculation operations, while some also include more advanced specialized instructions that can operate on multiple operands at a time.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Some CPU architectures include multiple AGUs so more than one address-calculation operation can be executed simultaneously, which brings further performance improvements due to the superscalar nature of advanced CPU designs.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, Intel incorporates multiple AGUs into its Sandy Bridge and Haswell microarchitectures, which increase bandwidth of the CPU memory subsystem by allowing multiple memory-access instructions to be executed in parallel.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Many microprocessors (in smartphones and desktop, laptop, server computers) have a memory management unit (MMU), translating logical addresses into physical RAM addresses, providing memory protection and paging abilities, useful for virtual memory.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The MMU is usually integrated in the processor but in some cases it is in a separate integrated circuit (IC).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Simpler processors, especially microcontrollers, usually do not include an MMU.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] A CPU cache is a memory used by the central processing unit (CPU) of a computer to reduce the average cost (time or energy) to access data from the main memory.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] A cache is a smaller, faster memory, closer to a processor core, which stores copies of the data from frequently used main memory locations.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Most CPUs have different independent caches, usually organized as a hierarchy of several cache levels (L1, L2, L3, L4, etc.).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Each ascending cache level is typically slower but larger than the preceding level with L1 being the fastest and the closest to the CPU.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] At the L1 level there are usually separate instruction and data caches.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Most modern (fast) CPUs (with few specialized exceptions) have multiple levels of CPU caches.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The first CPUs that used a cache had only one level of cache; unlike later level 1 caches, it was not split into L1d (for data) and L1i (for instructions).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Almost all current CPUs with caches have a split L1 cache.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] They also have L2 caches and, for larger processors, L3 caches as well.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The L2 cache is usually not split and acts as a common repository for the already split L1 cache.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Every core of a multi-core processor has a dedicated L2 cache and is usually not shared between the cores.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The L3 cache, and higher-level caches, are shared between the cores and are not split.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] An L4 cache is currently uncommon, and is generally on dynamic random-access memory (DRAM), rather than on static random-access memory (SRAM), on a separate die or chip.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] That was also the case historically with L1, while bigger chips have allowed integration of it and generally all cache levels, with the possible exception of the last level.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Each extra level of cache tends to be bigger and is optimized differently.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Other types of caches exist (that are not counted towards the "cache size" of the most important caches mentioned above), such as the translation lookaside buffer (TLB) that is part of the memory management unit (MMU) that most CPUs have.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Caches are generally sized in powers of two: 2, 8, 16 etc.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] KiB or MiB (for larger non-L1) sizes, although the IBM z13 has a 96 KiB L1 instruction cache.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Most CPUs are synchronous circuits, which means they employ a clock signal to pace their sequential operations.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The clock signal is produced by an external oscillator circuit that generates a consistent number of pulses each second in the form of a periodic square wave.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The frequency of the clock pulses determines the rate at which a CPU executes instructions and, consequently, the faster the clock, the more instructions the CPU will execute each second.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] To ensure proper operation of the CPU, the clock period is longer than the maximum time needed for all signals to propagate (move) through the CPU.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] In setting the clock period to a value well above the worst-case propagation delay, it is possible to design the entire CPU and the way it moves data around the "edges" of the rising and falling clock signal.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This has the advantage of simplifying the CPU significantly, both from a design perspective and a component-count perspective.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] However, it also carries the disadvantage that the entire CPU must wait on its slowest elements, even though some portions of it are much faster.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This limitation has largely been compensated for by various methods of increasing CPU parallelism (see below).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] However, architectural improvements alone do not solve all of the drawbacks of globally synchronous CPUs.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, a clock signal is subject to the delays of any other electrical signal.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Higher clock rates in increasingly complex CPUs make it more difficult to keep the clock signal in phase (synchronized) throughout the entire unit.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This has led many modern CPUs to require multiple identical clock signals to be provided to avoid delaying a single signal significantly enough to cause the CPU to malfunction.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Another major issue, as clock rates increase dramatically, is the amount of heat that is dissipated by the CPU.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The constantly changing clock causes many components to switch regardless of whether they are being used at that time.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] In general, a component that is switching uses more energy than an element in a static state.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Therefore, as clock rate increases, so does energy consumption, causing the CPU to require more heat dissipation in the form of CPU cooling solutions.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] One method of dealing with the switching of unneeded components is called clock gating, which involves turning off the clock signal to unneeded components (effectively disabling them).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] However, this is often regarded as difficult to implement and therefore does not see common usage outside of very low-power designs.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] One notable CPU design that uses extensive clock gating is the IBM PowerPC-based Xenon used in the Xbox 360; this reduces the power requirements of the Xbox 360.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Another method of addressing some of the problems with a global clock signal is the removal of the clock signal altogether.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] While removing the global clock signal makes the design process considerably more complex in many ways, asynchronous (or clockless) designs carry marked advantages in power consumption and heat dissipation in comparison with similar synchronous designs.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] While somewhat uncommon, entire asynchronous CPUs have been built without using a global clock signal.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Two notable examples of this are the ARM compliant AMULET and the MIPS R3000 compatible MiniMIPS.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Rather than totally removing the clock signal, some CPU designs allow certain portions of the device to be asynchronous, such as using asynchronous ALUs in conjunction with superscalar pipelining to achieve some arithmetic performance gains.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] While it is not altogether clear whether totally asynchronous designs can perform at a comparable or better level than their synchronous counterparts, it is evident that they do at least excel in simpler math operations.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This, combined with their excellent power consumption and heat dissipation properties, makes them very suitable for embedded computers.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Many modern CPUs have a die-integrated power managing module which regulates on-demand voltage supply to the CPU circuitry allowing it to keep balance between performance and power consumption.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Every CPU represents numerical values in a specific way.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, some early digital computers represented numbers as familiar decimal (base 10) numeral system values, and others have employed more unusual representations such as bi-quinary coded decimal (base 2–5) or ternary (base 3).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Nearly all modern CPUs represent numbers in binary form, with each digit being represented by some two-valued physical quantity such as a "high" or "low" voltage.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Related to numeric representation is the size and precision of integer numbers that a CPU can represent.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] In the case of a binary CPU, this is measured by the number of bits (significant digits of a binary encoded integer) that the CPU can process in one operation, which is commonly called *word size*, *bit width*, *data path width*, *integer precision*, or *integer size*.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] A CPU's integer size determines the range of integer values on which it can directly operate.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, an 8-bit CPU can directly manipulate integers represented by eight bits, which have a range of 256 (28) discrete integer values.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Integer range can also affect the number of memory locations the CPU can directly address (an address is an integer value representing a specific memory location).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, if a binary CPU uses 32 bits to represent a memory address then it can directly address 232 memory locations.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] To circumvent this limitation and for various other reasons, some CPUs use mechanisms (such as memory management or bank switching) that allow additional memory to be addressed.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] CPUs with larger word sizes require more circuitry and consequently are physically larger, cost more and consume more power (and therefore generate more heat).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] As a result, smaller 4- or 8-bit microcontrollers are commonly used in modern applications even though CPUs with much larger word sizes (such as 16, 32, 64, even 128-bit) are available.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] When higher performance is required, however, the benefits of a larger word size (larger data ranges and address spaces) may outweigh the disadvantages.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] A CPU can have internal data paths shorter than the word size to reduce size and cost.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] To gain some of the advantages afforded by both lower and higher bit lengths, many instruction sets have different bit widths for integer and floating-point data, allowing CPUs implementing that instruction set to have different bit widths for different portions of the device.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] For example, the IBM System/360 instruction set was primarily 32 bit, but supported 64-bit floating-point values to facilitate greater accuracy and range in floating-point numbers.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The System/360 Model 65 had an 8-bit adder for decimal and fixed-point binary arithmetic and a 60-bit adder for floating-point arithmetic.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Many later CPU designs use similar mixed bit width, especially when the processor is meant for general-purpose use where a reasonable balance of integer and floating-point capability is required.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The description of the basic operation of a CPU offered in the previous section describes the simplest form that a CPU can take.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This type of CPU, usually referred to as *subscalar*, operates on and executes one instruction on one or two pieces of data at a time, that is less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This process gives rise to an inherent inefficiency in subscalar CPUs.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Since only one instruction is executed at a time, the entire CPU must wait for that instruction to complete before proceeding to the next instruction.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] As a result, the subscalar CPU gets "hung up" on instructions which take more than one clock cycle to complete execution.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Even adding a second execution unit (see below) does not improve performance much; rather than one pathway being hung up, now two pathways are hung up and the number of unused transistors is increased.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This design, wherein the CPU's execution resources can operate on only one instruction at a time, can only possibly reach *scalar* performance (one instruction per clock cycle, IPC = 1).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] However, the performance is nearly always subscalar (less than one instruction per clock cycle, IPC < 1).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Attempts to achieve scalar and better performance have resulted in a variety of design methodologies that cause the CPU to behave less linearly and more in parallel.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Each methodology differs both in the ways in which they are implemented, as well as the relative effectiveness they afford in increasing the CPU's performance for an application.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] One of the simplest methods for increased parallelism is to begin the first steps of instruction fetching and decoding before the prior instruction finishes executing.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This is a technique known as instruction pipelining, and is used in almost all modern general-purpose CPUs.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Pipelining allows multiple instructions to be executed at a time by breaking the execution pathway into discrete stages.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This separation can be compared to an assembly line, in which an instruction is made more complete at each stage until it exits the execution pipeline and is retired.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Pipelining does, however, introduce the possibility for a situation where the result of the previous operation is needed to complete the next operation; a condition often termed data dependency conflict.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Therefore, pipelined processors must check for these sorts of conditions and delay a portion of the pipeline if necessary.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] A pipelined processor can become very nearly scalar, inhibited only by pipeline stalls (an instruction spending more than one clock cycle in a stage).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Improvements in instruction pipelining led to further decreases in the idle time of CPU components.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Designs that are said to be superscalar include a long instruction pipeline and multiple identical execution units, such as load–store units, arithmetic–logic units, floating-point units and address generation units.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] In a superscalar pipeline, instructions are read and passed to a dispatcher, which decides whether or not the instructions can be executed in parallel (simultaneously).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] If so, they are dispatched to execution units, resulting in their simultaneous execution.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] In general, the number of instructions that a superscalar CPU will complete in a cycle is dependent on the number of instructions it is able to dispatch simultaneously to execution units.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Most of the difficulty in the design of a superscalar CPU architecture lies in creating an effective dispatcher.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The dispatcher needs to be able to quickly determine whether instructions can be executed in parallel, as well as dispatch them in such a way as to keep as many execution units busy as possible.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This requires that the instruction pipeline is filled as often as possible and requires significant amounts of CPU cache.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] It also makes hazard-avoiding techniques like branch prediction, speculative execution, register renaming, out-of-order execution and transactional memory crucial to maintaining high levels of performance.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] By attempting to predict which branch (or path) a conditional instruction will take, the CPU can minimize the number of times that the entire pipeline must wait until a conditional instruction is completed.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Speculative execution often provides modest performance increases by executing portions of code that may not be needed after a conditional operation completes.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Out-of-order execution somewhat rearranges the order in which instructions are executed to reduce delays due to data dependencies.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] When a fraction of the CPU is superscalar, the part that is not suffers a performance penalty due to scheduling stalls.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The Intel P5 Pentium had two superscalar ALUs which could accept one instruction per clock cycle each, but its FPU could not.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Thus the P5 was integer superscalar but not floating point superscalar.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Intel's successor to the P5 architecture, P6, added superscalar abilities to its floating-point features.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Simple pipelining and superscalar design increase a CPU's ILP by allowing it to execute instructions at rates surpassing one instruction per clock cycle.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Most modern CPU designs are at least somewhat superscalar, and nearly all general purpose CPUs designed in the last decade are superscalar.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] In later years some of the emphasis in designing high-ILP computers has been moved out of the CPU's hardware and into its software interface, or instruction set architecture (ISA).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The strategy of the very long instruction word (VLIW) causes some ILP to become implied directly by the software, reducing the CPU's work in boosting ILP and thereby reducing design complexity.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Another strategy of achieving performance is to execute multiple threads or processes in parallel.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This area of research is known as parallel computing.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] In Flynn's taxonomy, this strategy is known as multiple instruction stream, multiple data stream (MIMD).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] One technology used for this purpose is multiprocessing (MP).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The initial type of this technology is known as symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), where a small number of CPUs share a coherent view of their memory system.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] In this scheme, each CPU has additional hardware to maintain a constantly up-to-date view of memory.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] By avoiding stale views of memory, the CPUs can cooperate on the same program and programs can migrate from one CPU to another.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] To increase the number of cooperating CPUs beyond a handful, schemes such as non-uniform memory access (NUMA) and directory-based coherence protocols were introduced in the 1990s.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] SMP systems are limited to a small number of CPUs while NUMA systems have been built with thousands of processors.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Initially, multiprocessing was built using multiple discrete CPUs and boards to implement the interconnect between the processors.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] When the processors and their interconnect are all implemented on a single chip, the technology is known as chip-level multiprocessing (CMP) and the single chip as a multi-core processor.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] It was later recognized that finer-grain parallelism existed with a single program.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] A single program might have several threads (or functions) that could be executed separately or in parallel.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Some of the earliest examples of this technology implemented input/output processing such as direct memory access as a separate thread from the computation thread.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] A more general approach to this technology was introduced in the 1970s when systems were designed to run multiple computation threads in parallel.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This technology is known as multi-threading (MT).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The approach is considered more cost-effective than multiprocessing, as only a small number of components within a CPU are replicated to support MT as opposed to the entire CPU in the case of MP.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] In MT, the execution units and the memory system including the caches are shared among multiple threads.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The downside of MT is that the hardware support for multithreading is more visible to software than that of MP and thus supervisor software like operating systems have to undergo larger changes to support MT.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] One type of MT that was implemented is known as temporal multithreading, where one thread is executed until it is stalled waiting for data to return from external memory.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] In this scheme, the CPU would then quickly context switch to another thread which is ready to run, the switch often done in one CPU clock cycle, such as the UltraSPARC T1.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Another type of MT is simultaneous multithreading, where instructions from multiple threads are executed in parallel within one CPU clock cycle.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] For several decades from the 1970s to early 2000s, the focus in designing high performance general purpose CPUs was largely on achieving high ILP through technologies such as pipelining, caches, superscalar execution, out-of-order execution, etc.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This trend culminated in large, power-hungry CPUs such as the Intel Pentium 4.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] By the early 2000s, CPU designers were thwarted from achieving higher performance from ILP techniques due to the growing disparity between CPU operating frequencies and main memory operating frequencies as well as escalating CPU power dissipation owing to more esoteric ILP techniques.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] CPU designers then borrowed ideas from commercial computing markets such as transaction processing, where the aggregate performance of multiple programs, also known as throughput computing, was more important than the performance of a single thread or process.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This reversal of emphasis is evidenced by the proliferation of dual and more core processor designs and notably, Intel's newer designs resembling its less superscalar P6 architecture.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] A less common but increasingly important paradigm of processors (and indeed, computing in general) deals with data parallelism.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The processors discussed earlier are all referred to as some type of scalar device.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] As the name implies, vector processors deal with multiple pieces of data in the context of one instruction.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This contrasts with scalar processors, which deal with one piece of data for every instruction.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Using Flynn's taxonomy, these two schemes of dealing with data are generally referred to as *single instruction* stream, *multiple data* stream (SIMD) and *single instruction* stream, *single data* stream (SISD), respectively.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The great utility in creating processors that deal with vectors of data lies in optimizing tasks that tend to require the same operation (for example, a sum or a dot product) to be performed on a large set of data.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Some classic examples of these types of tasks include multimedia applications (images, video and sound), as well as many types of scientific and engineering tasks.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Whereas a scalar processor must complete the entire process of fetching, decoding and executing each instruction and value in a set of data, a vector processor can perform a single operation on a comparatively large set of data with one instruction.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This is only possible when the application tends to require many steps which apply one operation to a large set of data.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Most early vector processors, such as the Cray-1, were associated almost exclusively with scientific research and cryptography applications.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] However, as multimedia has largely shifted to digital media, the need for some form of SIMD in general-purpose processors has become significant.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Shortly after inclusion of floating-point units started to become commonplace in general-purpose processors, specifications for and implementations of SIMD execution units also began to appear for general-purpose processors in the mid-1990s.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Some of these early SIMD specifications – like HP's Multimedia Acceleration eXtensions (MAX) and Intel's MMX – were integer-only.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This proved to be a significant impediment for some software developers, since many of the applications that benefit from SIMD primarily deal with floating-point numbers.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Progressively, developers refined and remade these early designs into some of the common modern SIMD specifications, which are usually associated with one instruction set architecture (ISA).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Some notable modern examples include Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE) and the PowerPC-related AltiVec (also known as VMX).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Many modern architectures (including embedded ones) often include hardware performance counters (HPC), which enables low-level (instruction-level) collection, benchmarking, debugging or analysis of running software metrics.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] HPC may also be used to discover and analyze unusual or suspicious activity of the software, such as return-oriented programming (ROP) or sigreturn-oriented programming (SROP) exploits etc.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This is usually done by software-security teams to assess and find malicious binary programs.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Many major vendors (such as IBM, Intel, AMD, and Arm) provide software interfaces (usually written in C/C++) that can be used to collect data from the CPU's registers in order to get metrics.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Operating system vendors also provide software like `perf` (Linux) to record, benchmark, or trace CPU events running kernels and applications.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Hardware counters provide a low-overhead method for collecting comprehensive performance metrics related to a CPU's core elements (functional units, caches, main memory, etc.) – a significant advantage over software profilers.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Additionally, they generally eliminate the need to modify the underlying source code of a program.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Because hardware designs differ between architectures, the specific types and interpretations of hardware counters will also change.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Most modern CPUs have privileged modes to support operating systems and virtualization.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Cloud computing can use virtualization to provide a **virtual central processing unit** (**vCPU**) for separate users; vCPU is not to be confused with a virtual private server (VPS).
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] A host is the virtual equivalent of a physical machine, on which a virtual system is operating.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] When there are several physical machines operating in tandem and managed as a whole, the grouped computing and memory resources form a cluster.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] In some systems, it is possible to dynamically add and remove from a cluster.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Resources available at a host and cluster level can be partitioned into resources pools with fine granularity.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The *performance* or *speed* of a processor depends on, among many other factors, the clock rate (generally given in multiples of hertz) and the instructions per clock (IPC), which together are the factors for the instructions per second (IPS) that the CPU can perform.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Many reported IPS values have represented "peak" execution rates on artificial instruction sequences with few branches, whereas realistic workloads consist of a mix of instructions and applications, some of which take longer to execute than others.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] The performance of the memory hierarchy also greatly affects processor performance, an issue barely considered in IPS calculations.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Because of these problems, various standardized tests, often called "benchmarks" for this purpose – such as SPECint – have been developed to attempt to measure the real effective performance in commonly used applications.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Processing performance of computers is increased by using multi-core processors, which essentially is plugging two or more individual processors (called *cores* in this sense) into one integrated circuit.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Ideally, a dual core processor would be nearly twice as powerful as a single core processor.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] In practice, the performance gain is far smaller, only about 50%, due to imperfect software algorithms and implementation.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Increasing the number of cores in a processor (i.e. dual-core, quad-core, etc.) increases the workload that can be handled.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This means that the processor can now handle numerous asynchronous events, interrupts, etc. which can take a toll on the CPU when overwhelmed.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] These cores can be thought of as different floors in a processing plant, with each floor handling a different task.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Sometimes, these cores will handle the same tasks as cores adjacent to them if a single core is not enough to handle the information.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Multi-core CPUs enhance a computer's ability to run several tasks simultaneously by providing additional processing power.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] However, the increase in speed is not directly proportional to the number of cores added.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] This is because the cores need to interact through specific channels, and this inter-core communication consumes a portion of the available processing speed.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Due to specific capabilities of modern CPUs, such as simultaneous multithreading and uncore, which involve sharing of actual CPU resources while aiming at increased utilization, monitoring performance levels and hardware use gradually became a more complex task.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] As a response, some CPUs implement additional hardware logic that monitors actual use of various parts of a CPU and provides various counters accessible to software; an example is Intel's *Performance Counter Monitor* technology.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Overclocking is a process of increasing the clock speed of a CPU (and other components) beyond their rated speeds.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Increasing a component's clock rate causes it to perform more operations per second.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Overclocking might increase CPU temperature and cause it to overheat, so most users do not overclock and leave the clock speed unchanged.
[src:intel-sgx/central-processing-unit-p02] Manufacturers may limit the degree to which a component can be overclocked, such as by limiting clock ratios, maximum power consumption, or both.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing proponents such as International Data Corporation, the Enterprise Strategy Group and Endpoint Technologies Associates state that the technology will make computers safer, less prone to viruses and malware, and thus more reliable from an end-user perspective.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] They also state that Trusted Computing will allow computers and servers to offer improved computer security over that which is currently available.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Opponents often state that this technology will be used primarily to enforce digital rights management policies (imposed restrictions to the owner) and not to increase computer security.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Chip manufacturers Intel and AMD, hardware manufacturers such as HP and Dell, and operating system providers such as Microsoft include Trusted Computing in their products if enabled.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Army requires that every new PC it purchases comes with a Trusted Platform Module (TPM).
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] As of July 3, 2007, so does virtually the entire United States Department of Defense.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The endorsement key is a 2048-bit RSA public and private key pair that is created randomly on the chip at manufacture time and cannot be changed.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The private key never leaves the chip, while the public key is used for attestation and for encryption of sensitive data sent to the chip, as occurs during the TPM_TakeOwnership command.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The TPM should be designed to make the extraction of this key by hardware analysis hard, but tamper resistance is not a strong requirement.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Memory curtaining extends common memory protection techniques to provide full isolation of sensitive areas of memory—for example, locations containing cryptographic keys.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Even the operating system does not have full access to curtained memory.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The exact implementation details are vendor specific.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Sealed storage protects private information by binding it to platform configuration information including the software and hardware being used.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] This means the data can be released only to a particular combination of software and hardware.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Sealed storage can be used for DRM enforcing.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] For example, users who keep a song on their computer that has not been licensed to be listened will not be able to play it.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Currently, a user can locate the song, listen to it, and send it to someone else, play it in the software of their choice, or back it up (and in some cases, use circumvention software to decrypt it).
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Alternatively, the user may use software to modify the operating system's DRM routines to have it leak the song data once, say, a temporary license was acquired.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Using sealed storage, the song is securely encrypted using a key bound to the trusted platform module so that only the unmodified and untampered music player on his or her computer can play it.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] In this DRM architecture, this might also prevent people from listening to the song after buying a new computer, or upgrading parts of their current one, except after explicit permission of the vendor of the song.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Remote attestation allows changes to the user's computer to be detected by authorized parties.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] For example, software companies can identify unauthorized changes to software, including users modifying their software to circumvent commercial digital rights restrictions.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] It works by having the hardware generate a certificate stating what software is currently running.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The computer can then present this certificate to a remote party to show that unaltered software is currently executing.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Numerous remote attestation schemes have been proposed for various computer architectures, including Intel, RISC-V, and ARM.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Remote attestation is usually combined with public-key encryption so that the information sent can only be read by the programs that requested the attestation, and not by an eavesdropper.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] To take the song example again, the user's music player software could send the song to other machines, but only if they could attest that they were running an authorized copy of the music player software.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] To preserve the privacy of attestation responders, Direct Anonymous Attestation has been proposed as a solution, which uses a group signature scheme to prevent revealing the identity of individual signers.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Proof of space (PoS) have been proposed to be used for malware detection, by determining whether the L1 cache of a processor is empty (e.g., has enough space to evaluate the PoSpace routine without cache misses) or contains a routine that resisted being evicted.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The Microsoft products Windows Vista, Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows RT make use of a Trusted Platform Module to facilitate BitLocker Drive Encryption.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Other known applications with runtime encryption and the use of secure enclaves include the Signal messenger and the e-prescription service ("E-Rezept") by the German government.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing would allow companies to create a digital rights management (DRM) system which would be very hard to circumvent, though not impossible.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Sealed storage could be used to prevent the user from opening the file with an unauthorized player or computer.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Remote attestation could be used to authorize play only by music players that enforce the record company's rules.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The music would be played from curtained memory, which would prevent the user from making an unrestricted copy of the file while it is playing, and secure I/O would prevent capturing what is being sent to the sound system.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Circumventing such a system would require either manipulation of the computer's hardware, capturing the analogue (and thus degraded) signal using a recording device or a microphone, or breaking the security of the system.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] New business models for use of software (services) over Internet may be boosted by the technology.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] By strengthening the DRM system, one could base a business model on renting programs for a specific time periods or "pay as you go" models.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] For instance, one could download a music file which could only be played a certain number of times before it becomes unusable, or the music file could be used only within a certain time period.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing could be used to combat cheating in online games.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Some players modify their game copy in order to gain unfair advantages in the game; remote attestation, secure I/O and memory curtaining could be used to determine that all players connected to a server were running an unmodified copy of the software.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing could be used to guarantee participants in a grid computing system are returning the results of the computations they claim to be instead of forging them.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] This would allow large scale simulations to be run (say a climate simulation) without expensive redundant computations to guarantee malicious hosts are not undermining the results to achieve the conclusion they want.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The Electronic Frontier Foundation and the Free Software Foundation criticize that trust in the underlying companies is not deserved and that the technology puts too much power and control into the hands of those who design systems and software.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] They also state that it may cause consumers to lose anonymity in their online interactions, as well as mandating technologies Trusted Computing opponents say are unnecessary.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] They suggest Trusted Computing as a possible enabler for future versions of mandatory access control, copy protection, and DRM.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Some security experts, such as Alan Cox and Bruce Schneier, have spoken out against Trusted Computing, believing it will provide computer manufacturers and software authors with increased control to impose restrictions on what users are able to do with their computers.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] There are concerns that Trusted Computing would have an anti-competitive effect on the IT market.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] There is concern amongst critics that it will not always be possible to examine the hardware components on which Trusted Computing relies, the Trusted Platform Module, which is the ultimate hardware system where the core 'root' of trust in the platform has to reside.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] If not implemented correctly, it presents a security risk to overall platform integrity and protected data.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The specifications, as published by the Trusted Computing Group, are open and are available for anyone to review.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] However, the final implementations by commercial vendors will not necessarily be subjected to the same review process.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] In addition, the world of cryptography can often move quickly, and that hardware implementations of algorithms might create an inadvertent obsolescence.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Trusting networked computers to controlling authorities rather than to individuals may create digital imprimaturs.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] One of the early motivations behind trusted computing was a desire by media and software corporations for stricter DRM technology to prevent users from freely sharing and using potentially copyrighted or private files without explicit permission.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] An example could be downloading a music file from a band: the band's record company could come up with rules for how the band's music can be used.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] For example, they might want the user to play the file only three times a day without paying additional money.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Also, they could use remote attestation to only send their music to a music player that enforces their rules: sealed storage would prevent the user from opening the file with another player that did not enforce the restrictions.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Memory curtaining would prevent the user from making an unrestricted copy of the file while it is playing, and secure output would prevent capturing what is sent to the sound system.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] A user who wanted to switch to a competing program might find that it would be impossible for that new program to read old data, as the information would be "locked in" to the old program.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] It could also make it impossible for the user to read or modify their data except as specifically permitted by the software.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The law in many countries allows users certain rights over data whose copyright they do not own (including text, images, and other media), often under headings such as fair use or public interest.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Depending on jurisdiction, these may cover issues such as whistleblowing, production of evidence in court, quoting or other small-scale usage, backups of owned media, and making a copy of owned material for personal use on other owned devices or systems.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The steps implicit in trusted computing have the practical effect of preventing users exercising these legal rights.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] A service that requires external validation or permission - such as a music file or game that requires connection with the vendor to confirm permission to play or use - is vulnerable to that service being withdrawn or no longer updated.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] A number of incidents have already occurred where users, having purchased music or video media, have found their ability to watch or listen to it suddenly stop due to vendor policy or cessation of service, or server inaccessibility, at times with no compensation.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Alternatively in some cases the vendor refuses to provide services in future which leaves purchased material only usable on the present -and increasingly obsolete- hardware (so long as it lasts) but not on any hardware that may be purchased in future.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Some opponents of Trusted Computing advocate "owner override": allowing an owner who is confirmed to be physically present to allow the computer to bypass restrictions and use the secure I/O path.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Such an override would allow remote attestation to a user's specification, e.g., to create certificates that say Internet Explorer is running, even if a different browser is used.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Instead of preventing software change, remote attestation would indicate when the software has been changed without owner's permission.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing Group members have refused to implement owner override.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Proponents of trusted computing believe that owner override defeats the trust in other computers since remote attestation can be forged by the owner.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Owner override offers the security and enforcement benefits to a machine owner, but does not allow them to trust other computers, because their owners could waive rules or restrictions on their own computers.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Under this scenario, once data is sent to someone else's computer, whether it be a diary, a DRM music file, or a joint project, that other person controls what security, if any, their computer will enforce on their copy of those data.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] This has the potential to undermine the applications of trusted computing to enforce DRM, control cheating in online games and attest to remote computations for grid computing.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Because a Trusted Computing equipped computer is able to uniquely attest to its own identity, it will be possible for vendors and others who possess the ability to use the attestation feature to zero in on the identity of the user of TC-enabled software with a high degree of certainty.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Such a capability is contingent on the reasonable chance that the user at some time provides user-identifying information, whether voluntarily, indirectly, or simply through inference of many seemingly benign pieces of data.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] (e.g. search records, as shown through simple study of the AOL search records leak).
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] One common way that information can be obtained and linked is when a user registers a computer just after purchase.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Another common way is when a user provides identifying information to the website of an affiliate of the vendor.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] While proponents of TC point out that online purchases and credit transactions could potentially be more secure as a result of the remote attestation capability, this may cause the computer user to lose expectations of anonymity when using the Internet.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Critics point out that this could have a chilling effect on political free speech, the ability of journalists to use anonymous sources, whistle blowing, political blogging and other areas where the public needs protection from retaliation through anonymity.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The TPM specification offers features and suggested implementations that are meant to address the anonymity requirement.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] By using a third-party Privacy Certification Authority (PCA), the information that identifies the computer could be held by a trusted third party.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Additionally, the use of direct anonymous attestation (DAA), introduced in TPM v1.2, allows a client to perform attestation while not revealing any personally identifiable or machine information.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The kind of data that must be supplied to the TTP in order to get the trusted status is at present not entirely clear, but the TCG itself admits that "attestation is an important TPM function with significant privacy implications".
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] It is, however, clear that both static and dynamic information about the user computer may be supplied (Ekpubkey) to the TTP (v1.1b), it is not clear what data will be supplied to the “verifier” under v1.2.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The static information will uniquely identify the endorser of the platform, model, details of the TPM, and that the platform (PC) complies with the TCG specifications .
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The dynamic information is described as software running on the computer.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] If a program like Windows is registered in the user's name this in turn will uniquely identify the user.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Another dimension of privacy infringing capabilities might also be introduced with this new technology; how often you use your programs might be possible information provided to the TTP.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] In an exceptional, however practical situation, where a user purchases a pornographic movie on the Internet, the purchaser nowadays, must accept the fact that he has to provide credit card details to the provider, thereby possibly risking being identified.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] With the new technology a purchaser might also risk someone finding out that he (or she) has watched this pornographic movie 1000 times.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] This adds a new dimension to the possible privacy infringement.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The extent of data that will be supplied to the TTP/Verifiers is at present not exactly known, only when the technology is implemented and used will we be able to assess the exact nature and volume of the data that is transmitted.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing requests that all software and hardware vendors will follow the technical specifications released by the Trusted Computing Group in order to allow interoperability between different trusted software stacks.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] However, since at least mid-2006, there have been interoperability problems between the TrouSerS trusted software stack (released as open source software by IBM) and Hewlett-Packard's stack.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Another problem is that the technical specifications are still changing, so it is unclear which is the standard implementation of the trusted stack.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] People have voiced concerns that trusted computing could be used to keep or discourage users from running software created by companies outside of a small industry group.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The concerns about trusted computing being used to shut out competition exist within a broader framework of consumers being concerned about using bundling of products to obscure prices of products and to engage in anti-competitive practices.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Trusted Computing is seen as harmful or problematic to independent and open source software developers.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] In the widely used public-key cryptography, creation of keys can be done on the local computer and the creator has complete control over who has access to it, and consequentially their own security policies.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] In some proposed encryption-decryption chips, a private/public key is permanently embedded into the hardware when it is manufactured, and hardware manufacturers would have the opportunity to record the key without leaving evidence of doing so.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] With this key it would be possible to have access to data encrypted with it, and to authenticate as it.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] It is trivial for a manufacturer to give a copy of this key to the government or the software manufacturers, as the platform must go through steps so that it works with authenticated software.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] A security breach breaking that chain of trust happened to a SIM card manufacturer Gemalto, which in 2010 was infiltrated by US and British spies, resulting in compromised security of cellphone calls.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] It is also critical that one be able to trust that the hardware manufacturers and software developers properly implement trusted computing standards.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Incorrect implementation could be hidden from users, and thus could undermine the integrity of the whole system without users being aware of the flaw.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Since 2004, most major manufacturers have shipped systems that have included Trusted Platform Modules, with associated BIOS support.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] In accordance with the TCG specifications, the user must enable the Trusted Platform Module before it can be used.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Processor manufacturers have included secure enclaves in their design such as ARM TrustZone, Intel Management Engine with SGX and AMD PSP with Secure Encrypted Virtualization.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The Linux kernel has included trusted computing support since version 2.6.13, and there are several projects to implement trusted computing for Linux.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] In January 2005, members of Gentoo Linux's "crypto herd" announced their intention of providing support for TC—in particular support for the Trusted Platform Module.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] There is also a TCG-compliant software stack for Linux named TrouSerS, released under an open source license.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] There are several open-source projects that facilitate the use of confidential computing technology, including EGo, EdgelessDB and MarbleRun from Edgeless Systems, as well as Enarx, which originates from security research at Red Hat.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Some limited form of trusted computing can be implemented on current versions of Microsoft Windows with third-party software.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Major cloud providers such as Microsoft Azure, AWS and Google Cloud Platform have virtual machines with trusted computing features available.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] The Intel Classmate PC (a competitor to the One Laptop Per Child) includes a Trusted Platform Module.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] PrivateCore vCage software can be used to attest x86 servers with TPM chips.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Google enforces Play Integrity API to Android devices with their bootloader unlocked.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Mobile T6 secure operating system simulates the TPM functionality in mobile devices using the ARM TrustZone technology.
[src:intel-sgx/remote-attestation] Samsung smartphones come equipped with Samsung Knox that depend on features like Secure Boot, TIMA, MDM, TrustZone and SE Linux.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] In computer security, a **side-channel attack** is a type of security exploit that uses information inadvertently leaked by a system—such as timing, power consumption, or electromagnetic or acoustic emissions—to gain unauthorized access to sensitive information.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] These attacks differ from those targeting flaws in the design of cryptographic protocols or algorithms (notwithstanding the fact that cryptanalysis may identify vulnerabilities relevant to both types of attacks).
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Some side-channel attacks require technical knowledge of the internal operation of the system, others such as differential power analysis are effective as black-box attacks.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Attempts to break a cryptosystem by deceiving or coercing people with legitimate access are not typically considered side-channel attacks: see social engineering and rubber-hose cryptanalysis.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] In all cases, the underlying principle is that physical effects caused by the operation of a cryptosystem (*on the side*) can provide useful extra information about secrets in the system, for example, the cryptographic key, partial state information, full or partial plaintexts and so forth.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] The term cryptophthora (secret degradation) is sometimes used to express the degradation of secret key material resulting from side-channel leakage.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] A **cache side-channel attack** works by monitoring security critical operations such as AES T-table entry or modular exponentiation or multiplication or memory accesses.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] The attacker then is able to recover the secret key depending on the accesses made (or not made) by the victim, deducing the encryption key.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Also, unlike some of the other side-channel attacks, this method does not create a fault in the ongoing cryptographic operation and is invisible to the victim.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] In 2017, two CPU vulnerabilities (dubbed Meltdown and Spectre) were discovered, which can use a cache-based side channel to allow an attacker to leak memory contents of other processes and the operating system itself.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] A *power analysis* attack can provide even more detailed information by observing the power consumption of a hardware device such as CPU or cryptographic circuit.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] These attacks are roughly categorized into simple power analysis (SPA) and differential power analysis (DPA).
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] One example is Collide+Power, which affects nearly all CPUs.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Other examples use machine learning approaches.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Fluctuations in current also generate radio waves, enabling attacks that analyze measurements of electromagnetic (EM) emanations.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] These attacks typically involve similar statistical techniques as power-analysis attacks.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] A *deep-learning-based side-channel attack*, using the power and EM information across multiple devices has been demonstrated with the potential to break the secret key of a different but identical device in as low as a single trace.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Historical analogues to modern side-channel attacks are known.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] A recently declassified NSA document reveals that as far back as 1943, an engineer with Bell telephone observed decipherable spikes on an oscilloscope associated with the decrypted output of a certain encrypting teletype.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] According to former MI5 officer Peter Wright, the British Security Service analyzed emissions from French cipher equipment in the 1960s.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] In the 1980s, Soviet eavesdroppers were suspected of having planted bugs inside IBM Selectric typewriters to monitor the electrical noise generated as the type ball rotated and pitched to strike the paper; the characteristics of those signals could determine which key was pressed.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Power consumption of devices causes heating, which is offset by cooling effects.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Temperature changes create thermally induced mechanical stress.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] This stress can create low level acoustic emissions from operating CPUs (about 10 kHz in some cases).
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Recent research by Shamir et al. has suggested that information about the operation of cryptosystems and algorithms can be obtained in this way as well.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] This is an *acoustic cryptanalysis attack*.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] If the surface of the CPU chip, or in some cases the CPU package, can be observed, infrared images can also provide information about the code being executed on the CPU, known as a *thermal-imaging attack*.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] An *optical side-channel attack* examples include gleaning information from the hard disk activity indicator to reading a small number of photons emitted by transistors as they change state.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Under the first category, displays with special shielding to lessen electromagnetic emissions, reducing susceptibility to TEMPEST attacks, are now commercially available.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Power line conditioning and filtering can help deter power-monitoring attacks, although such measures must be used cautiously, since even very small correlations can remain and compromise security.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Physical enclosures can reduce the risk of surreptitious installation of microphones (to counter acoustic attacks) and other micro-monitoring devices (against CPU power-draw or thermal-imaging attacks).
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Another countermeasure (still in the first category) is to jam the emitted channel with noise.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] For instance, a random delay can be added to deter timing attacks, although adversaries can compensate for these delays by averaging multiple measurements (or, more generally, using more measurements in the analysis).
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] When the amount of noise in the side channel increases, the adversary needs to collect more measurements.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Another countermeasure under the first category is to use security analysis software to identify certain classes of side-channel attacks that can be found during the design stages of the underlying hardware itself.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Timing attacks and cache attacks are both identifiable through certain commercially available security analysis software platforms, which allow for testing to identify the attack vulnerability itself, as well as the effectiveness of the architectural change to circumvent the vulnerability.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] The most comprehensive method to employ this countermeasure is to create a Secure Development Lifecycle for hardware, which includes utilizing all available security analysis platforms at their respective stages of the hardware development lifecycle.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] In the case of timing attacks against targets whose computation times are quantized into discrete clock cycle counts, an effective countermeasure against is to design the software to be isochronous, that is to run in an exactly constant amount of time, independently of secret values.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Such countermeasures can be difficult to implement in practice, since even individual instructions can have variable timing on some CPUs.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] One partial countermeasure against simple power attacks, but not differential power-analysis attacks, is to design the software so that it is "PC-secure" in the "program counter security model".
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] In a PC-secure program, the execution path does not depend on secret values.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] In other words, all conditional branches depend only on public information.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] On architectures where the instruction execution time is not data-dependent, a PC-secure program is also immune to timing attacks.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Another way in which code can be non-isochronous is that modern CPUs have a memory cache: accessing infrequently used information incurs a large timing penalty, revealing some information about the frequency of use of memory blocks.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Cryptographic code designed to resist cache attacks attempts to use memory in only a predictable fashion (like accessing only the input, outputs and program data, and doing so according to a fixed pattern).
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] For example, data-dependent table lookups must be avoided because the cache could reveal which part of the lookup table was accessed.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Other partial countermeasures attempt to reduce the amount of information leaked from data-dependent power differences.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Some operations use power that is correlated to the number of 1 bits in a secret value.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Using a constant-weight code (such as using Fredkin gates or dual-rail encoding) can reduce the leakage of information about the Hamming weight of the secret value, although exploitable correlations are likely to remain unless the balancing is perfect.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] This "balanced design" can be approximated in software by manipulating both the data and its complement together.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Several "secure CPUs" have been built as asynchronous CPUs; they have no global timing reference.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] While these CPUs were intended to make timing and power attacks more difficult, subsequent research found that timing variations in asynchronous circuits are harder to remove.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Recently, white-box modeling was utilized to develop a low-overhead generic circuit-level countermeasure against both EM as well as power side-channel attacks.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] To minimize the effects of the higher-level metal layers in an IC acting as more efficient antennas, the idea is to embed the crypto core with a signature suppression circuit, routed locally within the lower-level metal layers, leading towards both power and EM side-channel attack immunity.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] As a countermeasure for message encryption, **masking** (also known as **blinding**) is effective against all side-channel attacks.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] The principle of masking is to avoid manipulating any sensitive value y directly, but rather manipulate a sharing of it: a set of variables (called "shares") $y_{1},...,y_{d}$ such that $y=y_{1}\oplus ...\oplus y_{d}$ (where $\oplus$ is the XOR operation).
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] An attacker must recover all the values of the shares to get any meaningful information.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] Since the decrypting system chose r , it can compute its inverse modulo m to cancel out the factor r in the result and obtain $y^{d}$ , the actual result of the decryption.
[src:intel-sgx/side-channel-attack] For attacks that require collecting side-channel information from operations with data *controlled by the attacker*, blinding is an effective countermeasure, since the actual operation is executed on a randomized version of the data, over which the attacker has no control or even knowledge.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] SGX involves encryption by the CPU of a portion of memory (the *enclave*).
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] Data and code originating in the enclave are decrypted on the fly *within* the CPU, protecting them from being examined or read by other code, including code running at higher privilege levels such as the operating system and any underlying hypervisors.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] While this can mitigate many kinds of attacks, it does not protect against side-channel attacks.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] A pivot by Intel in 2021 resulted in the deprecation of SGX from the 11th and 12th generation Intel Core processors, but development continues on Intel Xeon for cloud and enterprise use.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] SGX was first introduced in 2015 with the sixth generation Intel Core microprocessors based on the Skylake microarchitecture.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] Support for SGX in the CPU is indicated in CPUID "Structured Extended feature Leaf", EBX bit 02, but its availability to applications requires BIOS/UEFI support and opt-in enabling which is not reflected in CPUID bits.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] This complicates the feature detection logic for applications.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] Emulation of SGX was added to an experimental version of the QEMU system emulator in 2014.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] In 2015, researchers at the Georgia Institute of Technology released an open-source simulator named "OpenSGX".
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] One example of SGX used in security was a demo application from wolfSSL using it for cryptography algorithms.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] Intel Goldmont Plus (Gemini Lake) microarchitecture also contains support for Intel SGX.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] Both in the 11th and 12th generations of Intel Core processors, SGX is listed as "Deprecated" and thereby not supported on "client platform" processors.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] This removed support of playing Ultra HD Blu-ray discs on officially licensed software, such as PowerDVD.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] On 27 March 2017 researchers at Austria's Graz University of Technology developed a proof-of-concept that can grab RSA keys from SGX enclaves running on the same system within five minutes by using certain CPU instructions in lieu of a fine-grained timer to exploit cache DRAM side-channels.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] One countermeasure for this type of attack was presented and published by Daniel Gruss et al. at the USENIX Security Symposium in 2017.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] Among other published countermeasures, one countermeasure to this type of attack was published on September 28, 2017, a compiler-based tool, DR.SGX, that claims to have superior performance with the elimination of the implementation complexity of other proposed solutions.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] The LSDS group at Imperial College London showed a proof of concept that the Spectre speculative execution security vulnerability can be adapted to attack the secure enclave.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] The Foreshadow attack, disclosed in August 2018, combines speculative execution and buffer overflow to bypass the SGX.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] A security advisory and mitigation for this attack, also called an L1 Terminal Fault, was originally issued on August 14, 2018 and updated May 11, 2021.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] On 8 February 2019, researchers at Austria's Graz University of Technology published findings which showed that in some cases it is possible to run malicious code from within the enclave itself.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] The exploit involves scanning through process memory in order to reconstruct a payload, which can then run code on the system.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] The paper claims that due to the confidential and protected nature of the enclave, it is impossible for antivirus software to detect and remove malware residing within it.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] Intel issued a statement, stating that this attack was outside the threat model of SGX, that they cannot guarantee that code run by the user comes from trusted sources, and urged consumers to only run trusted code.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] There is a proliferation of side-channel attacks plaguing modern computer architectures.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] Many of these attacks measure slight, nondeterministic variations in the execution of code, so the attacker needs many measurements (possibly tens of thousands) to learn secrets.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] However, the MicroScope attack allows a malicious OS to replay code an arbitrary number of times regardless of the program's actual structure, enabling dozens of side-channel attacks.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] In July 2022, Intel submitted a Linux patch called AEX-Notify to allow the SGX enclave programmer to write a handler for these types of events.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] Security researchers were able to inject timing specific faults into execution within the enclave, resulting in leakage of information.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] The attack can be executed remotely, but requires access to the privileged control of the processor's voltage and frequency.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] A security advisory and mitigation for this attack was originally issued on August 14, 2018 and updated on March 20, 2020.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] Load Value Injection injects data into a program aiming to replace the value loaded from memory which is then used for a short time before the mistake is spotted and rolled back, during which LVI controls data and control flow.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] A security advisory and mitigation for this attack was originally issued on March 10, 2020 and updated on May 11, 2021.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] SGAxe, an SGX vulnerability published in 2020, extends a speculative execution attack on cache, leaking content of the enclave.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] This allows an attacker to access private CPU keys used for remote attestation.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] In other words, a threat actor can bypass Intel's countermeasures to breach SGX enclaves' confidentiality.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] The SGAxe attack is carried out by extracting attestation keys from SGX's private quoting enclave that are signed by Intel.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] The attacker can then masquerade as legitimate Intel machines by signing arbitrary SGX attestation quotes.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] A security advisory and mitigation for this attack, also called a Processor Data Leakage or Cache Eviction, was originally issued January 27, 2020 and updated May 11, 2021.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] In 2022, security researchers discovered a vulnerability in the Advanced Programmable Interrupt Controller (APIC) that allows for an attacker with root/admin privileges to gain access to encryption keys via the APIC by inspecting data transfers from L1 and L2 cache.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] This vulnerability is the first architectural attack discovered on x86 CPUs.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] This differs from Spectre and Meltdown which use a noisy side channel.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] This exploit currently affects Intel Core 10th, 11th and 12th generations, and Xeon Ice Lake microprocessors.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] There has been a long debate on whether SGX enables creation of superior malware.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] Oxford University researchers published an article in October 2022 considering attackers' potential advantages and disadvantages by abusing SGX for malware development.
[src:intel-sgx/software-guard-extensions] Researchers conclude that while there might be temporary zero-day vulnerabilities to abuse in SGX ecosystem, the core principles and design features of Trusted Execution Environments (TEEs) make malware weaker than a malware-in-the-wild, TEEs make no major contributions to malware otherwise.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] A **trusted execution environment** (**TEE**) is a secure area of a main processor.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] It helps the code and data loaded inside it be protected with respect to confidentiality and integrity.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] Data confidentiality prevents unauthorized entities from outside the TEE from reading data, while code integrity prevents code in the TEE from being replaced or modified by unauthorized entities, which may also be the computer owner itself as in certain DRM schemes described in Intel SGX.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] This is done by implementing unique, immutable, and confidential architectural security, which offers hardware-based memory encryption that isolates specific application code and data in memory.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] This allows user-level code to allocate private regions of memory, called enclaves, which are designed to be protected from processes running at higher privilege levels.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] A TEE as an isolated execution environment provides security features such as isolated execution, integrity of applications executing with the TEE, and confidentiality of their assets.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] In general terms, the TEE offers an execution space that provides a higher level of security for trusted applications running on the device than a rich operating system (OS) and more functionality than a 'secure element' (SE).
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] The first security level, Profile 1, was targeted against only software attacks, while Profile 2, was targeted against both software and hardware attacks.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] Commercial TEE solutions based on ARM TrustZone technology, conforming to the TR1 standard, were later launched, such as Trusted Foundations developed by Trusted Logic.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] Work on the OMTP standards ended in mid-2010 when the group transitioned into the Wholesale Applications Community (WAC).
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] The OMTP standards, including those defining a TEE, are hosted by GSMA.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE typically consists of a hardware isolation mechanism plus a secure operating system running on top of that isolation mechanism, although the term has been used more generally to mean a protected solution.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] Whilst a GlobalPlatform TEE requires hardware isolation, others, such as EMVCo, use the term TEE to refer to both hardware and software-based solutions.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] FIDO uses the concept of TEE in the restricted operating environment for TEEs based on hardware isolation.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] Only trusted applications running in a TEE have access to the full power of a device's main processor, peripherals, and memory, while hardware isolation protects these from user-installed apps running in a main operating system.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] Software and cryptography inside the TEE protects the trusted applications contained within from each other.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] Service providers, mobile network operators (MNO), operating system developers, application developers, device manufacturers, platform providers, and silicon vendors are the main stakeholders contributing to the standardization efforts around the TEE.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] To prevent the simulation of hardware with user-controlled software, a so-called "hardware root of trust" is used.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] This is a set of private keys that are embedded directly into the chip during manufacturing; one-time programmable memory such as eFuses is usually used on mobile devices.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] The hardware is designed in a way that prevents all software not signed by the trusted party's key from accessing the privileged features.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] The public key of the vendor is provided at runtime and hashed; this hash is then compared to the one embedded in the chip.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] If the hash matches, the public key is used to verify a digital signature of trusted vendor-controlled firmware (such as a chain of bootloaders on Android devices or 'architectural enclaves' in SGX).
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] The trusted firmware is then used to implement remote attestation.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] When an application is attested, its untrusted components loads its trusted component into memory; the trusted application is protected from modification by untrusted components with hardware.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] A nonce is requested by the untrusted party from the verifier's server and is used as part of a cryptographic authentication protocol, proving integrity of the trusted application.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] The proof is passed to the verifier, which verifies it.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] A valid proof cannot be computed in simulated hardware (i.e.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] QEMU) because in order to construct it, access to the keys baked into hardware is required; only trusted firmware has access to these keys and/or the keys derived from them or obtained using them.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] Because only the platform owner is meant to have access to the data recorded in the foundry, the verifying party must interact with the service set up by the vendor.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] If the scheme is implemented improperly, the chip vendor can track which applications are used on which chip and selectively deny service by returning a message indicating that authentication has not passed.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] To simulate hardware in a way that enables it to pass remote authentication, an attacker would have to extract keys from the hardware, which is costly because of the equipment and technical skill required to execute it.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] For example, using focused ion beams, scanning electron microscopes, microprobing, and chip decapsulation is difficult, or even impossible, if the hardware is designed in such a way that reverse-engineering destroys the keys.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] In most cases, the keys are unique for each piece of hardware, so that a key extracted from one chip cannot be used by others (for example physically unclonable functions).
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] Note: Much TEE literature covers this topic under the definition "premium content protection," which is the preferred nomenclature of many copyright holders.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] Premium content protection is a specific use case of digital rights management (DRM) and is controversial among some communities, such as the Free Software Foundation.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] It is widely used by copyright holders to restrict the ways in which end users can consume content such as 4K high-definition films.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE is a suitable environment for protecting digitally encoded information (for example, HD films or audio) on connected devices such as smartphones, tablets, and HD televisions.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] This suitability comes from the ability of the TEE to deprive the owner of the device of access stored secrets, and the fact that there is often a protected hardware path between the TEE and the display and/or subsystems on devices.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE is used to protect the content once it is on the device.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] While the content is protected during transmission or streaming by the use of encryption, the TEE protects the content once it has been decrypted on the device by ensuring that decrypted content is not exposed to the environment not approved by the app developer or platform vendor.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] Mobile commerce applications such as: mobile wallets, peer-to-peer payments, contactless payments or using a mobile device as a point of sale (POS) terminal often have well-defined security requirements.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] In some scenarios, interaction with the end user is required, and this may require the user to expose sensitive information such as a PIN, password, or biometric identifier to the mobile OS as a means of authenticating the user.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE optionally offers a trusted user interface which can be used to construct user authentication on a mobile device.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] With the rise of cryptocurrency, TEEs are increasingly used to implement crypto-wallets, as they offer the ability to store tokens more securely than regular operating systems, and can provide the necessary computation and authentication applications.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE is well-suited for supporting biometric identification methods (facial recognition, fingerprint sensor, and voice authorization), which may be easier to use and harder to steal than PINs and passwords.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] A TEE is a good area within a mobile device to house the matching engine and the associated processing required to authenticate the user.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] The environment is designed to protect the data and establish a buffer against the non-secure apps located in mobile OSes.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] This additional security may help to satisfy the security needs of service providers in addition to keeping the costs low for handset developers.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE can be used by governments, enterprises, and cloud service providers to enable the secure handling of confidential information on mobile devices and on server infrastructure.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE offers a level of protection against software attacks generated in the mobile OS and assists in the control of access rights.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] It achieves this by housing sensitive, ‘trusted’ applications that need to be isolated and protected from the mobile OS and any malicious malware that may be present.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] Through utilizing the functionality and security levels offered by the TEE, governments, and enterprises can be assured that employees using their own devices are doing so in a secure and trusted manner.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] Likewise, server-based TEEs help defend against internal and external attacks against backend infrastructure.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] With the rise of software assets and reuses, modular programming is the most productive process to design software architecture, by decoupling the functionalities into small independent modules.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] As each module contains everything necessary to execute its desired functionality, the TEE allows the organization of the complete system featuring a high level of reliability and security, while preventing each module from vulnerabilities of the others.
[src:intel-sgx/trusted-execution-environment] In order for the modules to communicate and share data, TEE provides means to securely have payloads sent/received between the modules, using mechanisms such as object serialization, in conjunction with proxies.
